📘 Loops in DSA
🟢 Introduction

A loop is a control structure that allows repeated execution of a block of code until a condition is met.

In DSA, loops are used to traverse data structures and implement algorithms efficiently.

🟢 Why Loops are Important in DSA

Loops are used to:

Traverse arrays, lists, strings
Perform repeated calculations
Implement searching & sorting algorithms
Reduce code duplication

👉 Without loops → most DSA problems cannot be solved.

🟢 Types of Loops
🔹 1. for Loop (Most Used ⭐)
for (initialization; condition; update) {
    // code
}
Example:
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    printf("%d ", i);
}
🔹 2. while Loop
while (condition) {
    // code
}
Example:
int i = 0;
while (i < 5) {
    printf("%d ", i);
    i++;
}
🔹 3. do-while Loop
do {
    // code
} while (condition);
Example:
int i = 0;
do {
    printf("%d ", i);
    i++;
} while (i < 5);
🟢 Loop Flow Visualization
5
🟢 Loop Control Statements
🔹 break
Terminates loop immediately
for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if (i == 5) break;
}
🔹 continue
Skips current iteration
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    if (i == 2) continue;
    printf("%d ", i);
}
🟢 Nested Loops (VERY IMPORTANT 🔥)

Loop inside another loop.

for (int i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {
    for (int j = 1; j <= 3; j++) {
        printf("* ");
    }
    printf("\n");
}

👉 Used in:

Pattern problems
Matrix traversal
Sorting algorithms
🟢 Loops in DSA Algorithms
Example: Array Traversal
int arr[] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};

for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    printf("%d ", arr[i]);
}
Example: Sum of Array
int sum = 0;

for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    sum += arr[i];
}
🟢 Time Complexity Insight ⚡
Single loop → O(n)
Nested loops → O(n²)

👉 Loops directly impact algorithm efficiency.

🟢 Common Mistakes ❌
Infinite loops
Wrong condition
Off-by-one errors (i <= n vs i < n)
Forgetting update step


🟢 Conclusion

Loops are one of the most powerful tools in DSA.
Mastering loops is essential for solving problems efficiently and understanding algorithm complexity.
